{"info": {"author": "Guotai Wang", "author_email": "wguotai@gmail.com", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Programming Language :: Python", "Programming Language :: Python :: 2", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3"], "description": "# GeodisTK: Geodesic Distance Transform Toolkit for 2D and 3D Images\nGeodesic transformation of images can be implementated with two approaches: fast marching and raster scan. Fast marching is based on the iterative propagation of a pixel front with velocity F [1]. Raster scan is based on kernel operations that are sequentially applied over the image in multiple passes [2][3]. In GeoS [4], the authors proposed to use a 3x3 kernel for forward and backward passes for efficient geodesic distance transform, which was used for image segmentation. \n\n![ranster scan](./data/ranster_scan.png)\nRaster scan for geodesic distance transform. Image from [4].\n\nDeepIGeoS [5] proposed to combine geodesic distance transforms with convolutional neural networks for efficient interactive segmentation of 2D and 3D images. \n\n* [1] Sethian, James A. \"Fast marching methods.\" SIAM review 41, no. 2 (1999): 199-235.\n* [2] Borgefors, Gunilla. \"Distance transformations in digital images.\" CVPR, 1986\n* [3] Toivanen, Pekka J. \"New geodesic distance transforms for gray-scale images.\" Pattern Recognition Letters 17, no. 5 (1996): 437-450.\n* [4] Criminisi, Antonio, Toby Sharp, and Andrew Blake. \"Geos: Geodesic image segmentation.\" ECCV, 2008.\n* [5] Wang, Guotai, et al. \"[`DeepIGeoS: A deep interactive geodesic framework for medical image segmentation`](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/8370732).\"  TPAMI, 2018. \n\n![2D example](./data/2d_example.png)\n\nA comparison of fast marching and ranster scan for 2D geodesic distance transform. (d) shows the Euclidean distance and (e) is a mixture of Geodesic and Euclidean distance.\n\nThis toolkit provides a cpp implementation of fast marching and raster scan for 2D/3D geodesic and\nEuclidean distance transforms and a mixture of them, and proivdes a python interface to use it. This is part of the work of DeepIGeoS [5]. [`If you use our code, please cite this paper.`](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/8370732)\n\n\n### How to install\n1. Install this toolkit easily by typing [`pip install GeodisTK`](https://pypi.org/project/GeodisTK/)\n\n2. Alternatively, if you want to build from source files, download this package and run the following:\n```bash\npython setup.py build\npython setup.py install\n```\n\n### How to use\n1. See a 2D example, run `python demo2d.py`\n\n2. See a 3D example, run `python demo3d.py`", "description_content_type": "text/markdown", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "https://github.com/taigw/GeodisTK", "keywords": "", "license": "MIT", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "GeodisTK", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/GeodisTK/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/GeodisTK/", "project_urls": {"Homepage": "https://github.com/taigw/GeodisTK"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/GeodisTK/0.1.6/", "requires_dist": null, "requires_python": ">=3.6", "summary": "An open-source toolkit to calculate geodesic distance for 2D and 3D images", "version": "0.1.6", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <h1>GeodisTK: Geodesic Distance Transform Toolkit for 2D and 3D Images</h1>\n<p>Geodesic transformation of images can be implementated with two approaches: fast marching and raster scan. Fast marching is based on the iterative propagation of a pixel front with velocity F [1]. Raster scan is based on kernel operations that are sequentially applied over the image in multiple passes [2][3]. In GeoS [4], the authors proposed to use a 3x3 kernel for forward and backward passes for efficient geodesic distance transform, which was used for image segmentation.</p>\n<p><img alt=\"ranster scan\" src=\"https://warehouse-camo.ingress.cmh1.psfhosted.org/6836053f92a25a201b570180120041f738f02660/2e2f646174612f72616e737465725f7363616e2e706e67\">\nRaster scan for geodesic distance transform. Image from [4].</p>\n<p>DeepIGeoS [5] proposed to combine geodesic distance transforms with convolutional neural networks for efficient interactive segmentation of 2D and 3D images.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>[1] Sethian, James A. \"Fast marching methods.\" SIAM review 41, no. 2 (1999): 199-235.</li>\n<li>[2] Borgefors, Gunilla. \"Distance transformations in digital images.\" CVPR, 1986</li>\n<li>[3] Toivanen, Pekka J. \"New geodesic distance transforms for gray-scale images.\" Pattern Recognition Letters 17, no. 5 (1996): 437-450.</li>\n<li>[4] Criminisi, Antonio, Toby Sharp, and Andrew Blake. \"Geos: Geodesic image segmentation.\" ECCV, 2008.</li>\n<li>[5] Wang, Guotai, et al. \"<a href=\"https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/8370732\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>DeepIGeoS: A deep interactive geodesic framework for medical image segmentation</code></a>.\"  TPAMI, 2018.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img alt=\"2D example\" src=\"https://warehouse-camo.ingress.cmh1.psfhosted.org/042e2ddb5e997f15a283ca247ebb88b846613989/2e2f646174612f32645f6578616d706c652e706e67\"></p>\n<p>A comparison of fast marching and ranster scan for 2D geodesic distance transform. (d) shows the Euclidean distance and (e) is a mixture of Geodesic and Euclidean distance.</p>\n<p>This toolkit provides a cpp implementation of fast marching and raster scan for 2D/3D geodesic and\nEuclidean distance transforms and a mixture of them, and proivdes a python interface to use it. This is part of the work of DeepIGeoS [5]. <a href=\"https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/8370732\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>If you use our code, please cite this paper.</code></a></p>\n<h3>How to install</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Install this toolkit easily by typing <a href=\"https://pypi.org/project/GeodisTK/\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>pip install GeodisTK</code></a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Alternatively, if you want to build from source files, download this package and run the following:</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<pre>python setup.py build\npython setup.py install\n</pre>\n<h3>How to use</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>See a 2D example, run <code>python demo2d.py</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>See a 3D example, run <code>python demo3d.py</code></p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 7091307, "releases": {"0.1": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "554aa7e637f771743dda75a362bd2cd3", "sha256": "5fec65c9b458f5a522ec76f2662b4addbc51291e4f08e3695b977416408ad96f"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "geodisTK-0.1-py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "554aa7e637f771743dda75a362bd2cd3", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py3", "requires_python": ">=3.6", "size": 2937, "upload_time": "2019-12-17T09:00:15", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2019-12-17T09:00:15.254111Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/06/18/c3fe13f78888cf53d3ed49a923f5eb3cc6bdb29e2c71d390446080ea25eb/geodisTK-0.1-py3-none-any.whl", "yanked": false}, {"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "b2336667c8ebd2a3d16e810893fee776", "sha256": "b76b1897de773533e968103d55aea552286dd8698ecefce241116302de079c77"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "geodisTK-0.1.tar.gz", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "b2336667c8ebd2a3d16e810893fee776", "packagetype": "sdist", "python_version": "source", "requires_python": ">=3.6", "size": 2413, "upload_time": "2019-12-17T09:00:17", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2019-12-17T09:00:17.655595Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/b3/a5/331f9a19d15711fc53769f262742ebf518ee48ad5ccc0ef718517fb77ddd/geodisTK-0.1.tar.gz", "yanked": false}], "0.1.1": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "680ce788d048bc3a88a4b46adb5b5994", "sha256": "f947ff2d0803912c00e1caed98efe17b751c936f38f68e801ea435be416c55b4"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "geodisTK-0.1.1-py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_dig